WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.560
We are so excited to be here.

00:00:08.560 --> 00:00:09.560
I'm Nicole Jardine.

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:13.120
I'm the Chief Data Officer for the Cook County Assessor's Office.

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:16.400
Soon I'll introduce Dan, our Director of Data Science.

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:22.879
And right off the bat, does anyone here, does anyone currently live in Chicago ever lived

00:00:22.879 --> 00:00:24.280
in the Chicagoland area?

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:27.719
Oh wow, okay, so about 10% of you, okay.

00:00:27.719 --> 00:00:28.920
We're excited to answer questions.

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:30.480
We love to talk about this topic.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:36.200
We have time at the end to talk about anything related to Chicago home ownership.

00:00:36.200 --> 00:00:41.000
Today Dan and I are going to talk about something that affects equity, housing affordability,

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.040
and generational wealth for a couple million people here in Chicago and the surrounding

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:46.360
suburbs.

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:49.220
And that thing is property taxes.

00:00:49.220 --> 00:00:53.599
Property tax bills here in Illinois depend in part on the government's assessment of

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:56.680
how much your property is currently worth.

00:00:56.880 --> 00:01:03.000
Just to set the stage a little bit, in Chicago in 2015, the average home was assessed as

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:10.279
if it was worth roughly $237k, and the average homeowner paid an average of about $3,600

00:01:10.279 --> 00:01:14.199
in property taxes.

00:01:14.199 --> 00:01:21.480
But starting in 2017, researchers at the University of Chicago and journalists at the Chicago

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:29.279
Tribune, ProPublica, and the New York Times identified a problem, and that problem was

00:01:29.279 --> 00:01:34.000
about property taxes, and specifically about the way that assessors throughout the country

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.120
were assessing property values.

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:42.000
The problem was identified using something that's called a ratio study.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:47.019
So the assessor's job in Illinois is to have assessments that follow the market every couple

00:01:47.019 --> 00:01:48.019
of years.

00:01:48.019 --> 00:01:52.540
The assessor assesses property values and adjusts them so that they're roughly in line

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:55.540
with where the real estate market has actually gone.

00:01:55.540 --> 00:01:59.660
And in a ratio study, you take the properties that have actually sold, which is roughly

00:01:59.660 --> 00:02:04.260
5% or so of homes here in any given year, and you compare the estimated value of that

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:08.779
property to its actual sale price.

00:02:08.779 --> 00:02:15.020
And this is a New York Times graphic, we've done some light modifications, and that ratio

00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:17.179
should be roughly 1.

00:02:17.179 --> 00:02:22.619
And what the New York Times and Chicago Tribune and others have found is that in the past,

00:02:22.619 --> 00:02:25.100
an average home was right around that 1 mark.

00:02:25.100 --> 00:02:28.339
That's about where it should be.

00:02:28.339 --> 00:02:29.779
But what about other homes?

00:02:29.779 --> 00:02:33.619
It's really important to think about homes on the other side of the distribution, not

00:02:33.619 --> 00:02:35.300
just the average homes.

00:02:35.300 --> 00:02:39.539
So here's an example of a modest home on the south side of Chicago.

00:02:39.539 --> 00:02:43.160
Let's say in 2015, it sold for about $50K.

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:49.080
On the other hand of that distribution, we have a nice home on the North Shore that maybe

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:51.559
sold for more like a million dollars.

00:02:51.559 --> 00:02:54.880
And the fundamental question is, what's that assessment ratio?

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:57.039
It's going to be close to 1.

00:02:57.039 --> 00:02:59.720
Well, we're here because...

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:06.080
So what that would mean, just to unpack that ratio a little more, if that 50K home actually

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:12.039
was assessed at 75K, that would mean a ratio of 1.5.

00:03:12.039 --> 00:03:16.880
And if that home that sold for a million dollars was assessed as if it was worth 800K,

00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:21.520
that would mean a ratio of 0.8.

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:24.080
Here's what the New York Times actually published.

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:31.360
There was a higher ratio of assessments to sale price for the homes with lower sale values.

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:37.000
So these homes that are on the more affordable side of the price spectrum were historically,

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.559
according to this reporting, over-assessed.

00:03:39.559 --> 00:03:40.559
That can lead to over-taxation.

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:46.320
And on the flip side, these homes that are these higher-priced homes were also being

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:49.160
under-assessed, leading to under-taxation.

00:03:49.160 --> 00:03:50.839
That's the problem.

00:03:50.839 --> 00:03:53.119
The Chicago Tribune referred to this as the tax divide.

00:03:53.119 --> 00:03:55.520
And that tax divide is why we're here.

00:03:55.520 --> 00:04:01.039
So again, the issue, according to the Tribune, as they stated it, is Cook County failed to

00:04:01.039 --> 00:04:03.880
value homes accurately for years.

00:04:03.880 --> 00:04:08.559
And the result was a property tax system that harmed the poor and helped the rich.

00:04:08.559 --> 00:04:13.960
The problem lies with the fundamentally flawed way that the County Assessor's Office valued

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:16.880
property.

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:17.880
So what's the cause?

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:20.359
It could actually be a number of interesting causes.

00:04:20.359 --> 00:04:24.600
Could be issues with the characteristics data that the Assessor's Office uses to estimate

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:26.480
property values.

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:31.839
It could be issues with the way other offices actually adjust assessed values.

00:04:31.839 --> 00:04:34.480
But we're here today because we want to talk about one of those issues, and one of those

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:36.040
is about the modeling.

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:41.880
So recall that the Assessor's Office uses sales, again, 5% of sales in a given year,

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:43.839
to estimate property values for everyone.

00:04:43.839 --> 00:04:46.559
In the past, this was done with regression modeling.

00:04:46.559 --> 00:04:50.079
This is actually a snippet of code.

00:04:50.079 --> 00:04:57.459
It was closed source, SPSS, OLS-based models, and, you know, we're talking 50,000 lines

00:04:57.459 --> 00:05:03.720
of manual fixed effects, property-specific overrides, and more.

00:05:03.720 --> 00:05:08.320
After the Tax Divide was published, voters elected a new Assessor, a new County Assessor,

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:15.279
Fritz Kege, and Fritz started the Data Department.

00:05:15.279 --> 00:05:17.880
The Data Department's first Chief Data Officer was Rob Ross.

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:24.119
I'm the current Chief Data Officer, and Dan and William and I have been on this journey

00:05:24.119 --> 00:05:26.359
together for about four years.

00:05:26.359 --> 00:05:31.279
And we're here because tech people and academics recognize that this is a data and a modeling

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:34.320
problem, and that maybe we could actually help solve it.

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:40.079
So our goal was to improve the model and transparency, and right now I'm super excited to hand it

00:05:40.079 --> 00:05:43.600
off to Dan, who's going to tell us about the model.

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:51.119
All right, hello, everyone.

00:05:51.119 --> 00:05:52.320
I am Dan Snow.

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:55.959
I'm the Director of Data Science at the Assessor's Office.

00:05:55.959 --> 00:06:01.720
And so Nicole has described the problem, basically lower-value properties broadly were

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:06.399
over-assessed, higher-value ones broadly were under-assessed.

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:10.399
I am going to talk about what we did to fix it.

00:06:10.399 --> 00:06:13.559
So the first thing we did was we got rid of the SPSS model.

00:06:13.559 --> 00:06:16.239
That is gone.

00:06:16.239 --> 00:06:20.440
And we replaced it with R. And if you would like to see what that model actually looks

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:24.619
like, you can visit this GitHub repo at the top.

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:29.140
That is the actual production model that is running right now.

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:33.339
Go through the README, check it out.

00:06:33.339 --> 00:06:40.380
We also moved from a closed-source, fully opaque model to one that is completely open-source

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:43.160
and that includes data to replicate it.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:47.859
So again, at that link at the top, this is the live-running model.

00:06:47.859 --> 00:06:52.100
On that repo, you can also find all of the data necessary to run the full pipeline to

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:58.500
get the values that we basically mailed to taxpayers with some adjustments.

00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:06.619
And we swapped out the old OLS model to a LightGBM-based, county-wide, tree-based model.

00:07:06.619 --> 00:07:11.540
So the old system had a sort of regimes-based OLS model.

00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:14.540
Different regions had different regressions.

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:20.579
Now one big model for the entire county using LightGBM.

00:07:20.579 --> 00:07:24.459
And to see what that actually looks like, this is the old code.

00:07:24.459 --> 00:07:29.480
It was, you know, 50,000-some lines of this, probably more.

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:33.980
You can see that there are no comments whatsoever.

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:42.179
It is basically just constructing manual time-fixed effects and then doing a regression on those.

00:07:42.179 --> 00:07:44.820
All of the code looked roughly like this.

00:07:44.820 --> 00:07:48.220
It was very unintelligible.

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:50.579
In 2019, the first thing we did was replace it.

00:07:50.579 --> 00:07:57.220
We replaced it with Base R because Tidy Models was very nascent at that time.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:07:59.859
And that code looked a lot like this.

00:07:59.859 --> 00:08:05.779
It improved the performance of the model pretty substantially, but this is not super easy

00:08:05.779 --> 00:08:07.100
code to read.

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:11.359
It was not especially replicable outside of our office.

00:08:11.359 --> 00:08:14.619
And so we needed something better.

00:08:14.619 --> 00:08:20.619
So in 21, we replaced that Base R system with Tidy Models, and the code looked like

00:08:20.619 --> 00:08:21.980
this.

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:25.380
Much more commenting, much simpler.

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:30.739
And we continued down that path to now, if you're looking at the code today, looks something

00:08:30.739 --> 00:08:32.900
like this.

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:40.380
So big improvement, and we will talk about what that actually gained us in terms of performance.

00:08:40.380 --> 00:08:41.900
That's what the model sort of looks like.

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:45.299
These are some of the things that go into the model.

00:08:45.299 --> 00:08:47.419
This is a regression on sale price, right?

00:08:47.419 --> 00:08:52.219
So sale price is the outcome, the thing that we are trying to predict.

00:08:52.219 --> 00:08:57.619
And the predictors are sort of things that you would expect for a sale price regression.

00:08:57.619 --> 00:09:03.539
They're like the size of the property, the year it was built, and basically where it

00:09:03.539 --> 00:09:04.539
is.

00:09:04.539 --> 00:09:06.460
Those are the big three.

00:09:06.460 --> 00:09:11.580
Those are indicated in blue with the lightning bolt, and all of the stuff in green is stuff

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:16.900
that we have added to the assessor's system of record database.

00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:22.859
So these are spatial features and stuff that we've imputed, or data that we have collected,

00:09:22.859 --> 00:09:28.200
and added with the goal of improving the accuracy and performance of the model.

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:36.260
The things in red are things that we are interested in collecting or have been asked about, but

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:39.179
for a number of reasons have not been able to include.

00:09:39.179 --> 00:09:43.179
All right, but what about tidy models?

00:09:43.179 --> 00:09:45.260
This is supposed to be a tidy models talk.

00:09:45.260 --> 00:09:47.859
So how do we actually use tidy models?

00:09:47.859 --> 00:09:54.460
Well, as I said, tidy models has fully replaced our sort of base R modeling code base.

00:09:54.460 --> 00:09:58.659
And that has been a huge, huge boon for us.

00:09:58.659 --> 00:10:04.659
It has completely abstracted away all of the complicated ML logic that used to be in that

00:10:04.659 --> 00:10:12.500
old code base, and that is stuff like cross-validation, you know, tuning hyperparameters, all sorts

00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:14.299
of things like that.

00:10:14.299 --> 00:10:18.859
It has allowed us to move much, much quicker and with more confidence, so we can sort of

00:10:18.859 --> 00:10:22.859
focus on the feature engineering and data collection side of things rather than being

00:10:22.859 --> 00:10:28.219
worried about shooting ourselves in the feet at every step.

00:10:28.219 --> 00:10:34.479
And importantly for us, it has also made the code much more understandable.

00:10:34.479 --> 00:10:37.280
We are a public agency, right?

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:43.159
And we want the code to be intelligible to the greatest number of people possible.

00:10:43.159 --> 00:10:49.039
I think that tidy models helps us accomplish that by putting it into a standardized framework

00:10:49.039 --> 00:10:54.640
that other people are familiar with.

00:10:54.640 --> 00:11:00.520
And it has just unlocked sort of more advanced features for us like easier hyperparameter

00:11:00.520 --> 00:11:07.200
optimization and better, cleaner feature engineering.

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:10.320
One example of that, time-based cross-validation.

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:14.919
So this is sort of how we do our cross-validation split using our data.

00:11:14.919 --> 00:11:21.239
It's like an expanding window of the training set with the last 10% held out as a validation

00:11:21.239 --> 00:11:22.760
set.

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:28.039
This is not something that would be super easy to program outside of tidy models, although

00:11:28.039 --> 00:11:32.359
we tried.

00:11:32.359 --> 00:11:35.280
We also made an R package.

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:37.960
This is our R package called lightsnip.

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:46.599
It is basically a shim between light GBM and parsnip to allow us to do all sorts of fun

00:11:46.599 --> 00:11:51.479
things similar to bonsai, if you're familiar with that package.

00:11:51.479 --> 00:11:57.520
We made it because we wanted to use some of light GBM's more advanced features.

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:01.000
Specifically, we wanted to use early stopping.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:06.320
So if you are training a model and after a certain point, the model is not improving

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:11.479
in performance, light GBM can automatically stop further training rounds and save you

00:12:11.479 --> 00:12:13.840
a lot of time.

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:19.760
In our case, implementing early stopping decreased our training time by like roughly two-thirds.

00:12:19.919 --> 00:12:26.000
This was a huge boon for us as a full training run with cross-validation was taking like

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:32.640
60 or 70 hours.

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:34.000
That's what we did.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:39.000
Now let's go back to our example properties that Nicole showed.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.239
These are actually real properties in Chicago.

00:12:41.239 --> 00:12:50.880
So in 2015, that property in the lowest decile, that was assessed for 53K.

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:53.559
Its 2021 estimate was lower than that.

00:12:53.559 --> 00:12:56.919
It was around 34K.

00:12:56.919 --> 00:13:01.640
And it sold in 22 for 33K.

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:07.840
So it had a ratio of right around one.

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:14.280
That larger property was actually the Home Alone house, which is in Winnetka.

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:20.719
And it sold in 2012 for around $1.56 million.

00:13:20.719 --> 00:13:27.440
Its estimate in 2018 before the new model, to be clear, was around $1.5 million.

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:31.780
But if you are familiar with property markets at all, and especially the property market

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:35.400
after the Great Recession, that does not make sense.

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:39.080
It should probably be higher than that.

00:13:39.080 --> 00:13:46.960
So its 2022 estimate was $2.3 million, which we cannot calculate a ratio on because we

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:49.280
don't have a recent sale.

00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:54.520
But we think that it is much closer to its actual market value.

00:13:54.520 --> 00:13:58.200
So that's the micro level results.

00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:01.400
On the macro level, this is a map of Chicago.

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:07.440
For those of you familiar with the map of Chicago, it probably looks very similar.

00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:13.840
Broadly speaking, the change in the modeling and some other things had the result of decreased

00:14:13.840 --> 00:14:20.039
assessments and ultimately tax bills on the south and west side of the city.

00:14:20.039 --> 00:14:21.039
Will that trend hold?

00:14:21.039 --> 00:14:23.679
It is hard to say.

00:14:23.679 --> 00:14:29.119
This map is going to change in 2024 since Chicago is reassessed every three years.

00:14:29.239 --> 00:14:36.719
We are preparing to do the 2024 model right now.

00:14:36.719 --> 00:14:42.599
Other things that we have done, nearly all of the assessor's data is now online and public.

00:14:42.599 --> 00:14:45.479
You can visit this link if you want to check it out.

00:14:45.479 --> 00:14:51.479
We have a public data portal, all sorts of property characteristics, tax history, spatial

00:14:51.479 --> 00:14:54.320
stuff that we've imputed, tons of things.

00:14:54.320 --> 00:15:01.520
I cannot express to you how big of a change this is from the old office.

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:09.039
We also publish a bunch of open source R and Python packages.

00:15:09.039 --> 00:15:14.679
These are mostly things related to assessment and property taxes, but they are very useful

00:15:14.679 --> 00:15:19.760
for academics and journalists in the space.

00:15:19.760 --> 00:15:39.119
And we do public reporting on assessments, their quality and accuracy, which are just

00:15:39.119 --> 00:15:42.780
available on the website.

00:15:42.780 --> 00:15:45.960
And so what is the point of all this?

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:48.359
What is the lessons to take away?

00:15:48.359 --> 00:15:56.159
To me, our work is proof, it is a case study of the effectiveness of technical teams in

00:15:56.159 --> 00:15:57.659
local government.

00:15:57.659 --> 00:16:04.359
I think that if you can get into the right place with the right people at the right time

00:16:04.359 --> 00:16:09.479
with a lot of leverage, you can make a huge impact in local government.

00:16:09.479 --> 00:16:16.280
And I would encourage anyone on the fence to try joining us because data skills are

00:16:16.280 --> 00:16:20.760
very desperately needed inside of state and local governments.

00:16:20.760 --> 00:16:24.000
Cannot express to you how true that is.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:30.640
And that is in all sorts of different areas like operations, policymaking, program evaluation,

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:33.320
tons of different places.

00:16:33.320 --> 00:16:39.159
And if you are really a glutton for punishment, you can join us in the assessment industry

00:16:39.159 --> 00:16:43.880
because this problem that we described about Chicago, this is nationwide.

00:16:43.880 --> 00:16:48.280
These are other graphs from that same New York Times article from other cities.

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:53.200
And you can see that their ratio curves look equally bad.

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:57.799
So if you're interested in learning more, I will take questions, and Nicole and I will

00:16:57.799 --> 00:17:00.640
stick around after the talk to chat.

00:17:00.640 --> 00:17:06.560
I also have some rare light GBM hex stickers, if anyone wants them.

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:09.439
So thank you, and I will be happy to take questions.

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:17.239
Big thank you, Dan and Nicole.

00:17:17.239 --> 00:17:19.400
And we have time for questions.

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:20.400
And we have a lot of questions.

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:21.400
Oh, great.

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:22.400
Oh.

00:17:22.400 --> 00:17:27.400
So, how much were you inspired by private companies like Zillow and Redfin, who also

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:28.400
do assessment?

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:30.880
Or where did you go to figure out how to do this?

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:33.800
Oh, that is a great question.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:36.400
I mean, significantly inspired.

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:40.079
They're building very similar predictive models.

00:17:40.079 --> 00:17:43.520
They're not predicting exactly the same thing.

00:17:43.520 --> 00:17:47.520
We are predicting the universe of all properties.

00:17:47.520 --> 00:17:52.000
Zillow is sort of predicting the universe of properties that are going to sell.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.719
And so they're different markets, not necessarily perfectly analogous.

00:17:55.719 --> 00:18:02.400
I think that our job is actually harder, personally, because, yes, we just have to cover a much

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:05.280
wider swath of properties.

00:18:05.280 --> 00:18:06.280
Yeah.

00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:07.280
Okay.

00:18:07.280 --> 00:18:08.560
Their blog is cool, though.

00:18:08.560 --> 00:18:09.560
Their blog is very cool.

00:18:09.560 --> 00:18:12.300
And they have a neat model.

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:16.739
So when switching from the old SPSS model to the new tidy models, did you discover that

00:18:16.739 --> 00:18:23.339
certain variables were placed with too much or too little importance in the past?

00:18:23.339 --> 00:18:25.739
No, I don't think so.

00:18:25.739 --> 00:18:31.380
I think generally the things that you would expect to be important to property values

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:33.979
stayed about the same in terms of their importance.

00:18:33.979 --> 00:18:35.939
It is exactly the things I said before.

00:18:35.939 --> 00:18:42.619
It is the size of the property, its relative age, and where it is.

00:18:42.619 --> 00:18:46.859
Those are sort of the big determinants of property value almost anywhere.

00:18:46.859 --> 00:18:48.699
Okay.

00:18:48.699 --> 00:18:49.699
One more question.

00:18:49.699 --> 00:18:54.859
Do you use any model explainability methods, for example, to help with conversation with

00:18:54.859 --> 00:18:57.619
public stakeholders?

00:18:57.619 --> 00:19:03.859
We do, although we have not made a lot of those results public, and we are sort of working

00:19:03.859 --> 00:19:04.859
on that.

00:19:04.859 --> 00:19:08.300
I'm happy to answer questions on that afterwards.

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:09.300
Thank you so much.

00:19:09.300 --> 00:19:10.300
Awesome.

00:19:10.300 --> 00:19:10.300


